{"cid":"Ugxl2GG93fUynhnXIiB4AaABAg","replyToCid":null,"type":"comment","publishedTimeText":"5 hours ago","comment":"Initially, the A330 didn't sell that well because its range was only just over 5,500 nautical miles. That's useful for transatlantic routes between the US East Coast to central Europe but not much else in terms of long-distance flights. Hence the push for the smaller A330-200 with its range of 6,400 nautical miles, which DID become a very successful model for Airbus because its range meant it could fly many transoceanic routes.

Interestingly, the original A350 proposal from 2004 was essentially an A330 with more fuel capacity and new, much more efficient engines. But Qatar Airways wanted more out of the plane, and as such Airbus shelved that original proposal in favor of what became the A350XWB, a clean-sheet airplane design. But the much higher per-plane cost of the A350XWB was not acceptable to many airlines, though.

The A330neo came about because airlines still wanted a larger twin-engine widebody at lower cost. Given the much lower development cost (since it was essentially an A330 with new wings and engines, close to the original A350 proposal), Airbus went ahead with the project, securing an order from a small number of airlines (TAP Air Portugal being the first). But the A330-900neo became an unexpected success, mostly because of its 7,200 nautical mile range, which made it ideal as a 777-200ER successor. This is why A330-900neo sales have been surprisingly good.","author":"@Sacto1654","authorIsChannelOwner":false,"replyCount":0,"voteCount":0,"hasCreatorHeart":false,"videoId":"wJYBgzTT47g","pageUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wJYBgzTT47g","commentsCount":30,"title":"The Real Story Behind The Airbus A330 - Full Documentary"}

{"cid":"UgwKOBueThX-TUoTR5x4AaABAg.AT267-kXVrEAT2izXnhsdK","replyToCid":"UgwKOBueThX-TUoTR5x4AaABAg","type":"reply","publishedTimeText":"5 hours ago","comment":"I am not sure about this question, but I have two answers.

First, If I would be the only passanger probably I would sleep along the flight like I always do.

Second, If the plane is mine and is empty like in the short situation i would still send it out if the schedule is made already cause canceling would cost more than the fuel to the destination, as a company ur plane is not rentfree on any airport you must pay ur stay/place so the longer you stay or you go off schedule the more you pay especially on busy airports.","author":"@Legolaslotr","authorIsChannelOwner":false,"replyCount":0,"voteCount":0,"hasCreatorHeart":false,"videoId":"r8IAYaRLz1M","pageUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/shorts/r8IAYaRLz1M","commentsCount":3,"title":"The Airline Made A Mistake They'll Never Forget 😱✈️ | (@natalie.wolfley)"}

{"cid":"Ugxt5gUni3eE3WRga5F4AaABAg","replyToCid":null,"type":"comment","publishedTimeText":"23 hours ago","comment":"Hokkaido has some of the best skiing on the planet and the prices are ridiculously lower than for example Aspen or Jackson Hole to the point that a return ticket to Japan and all other expenses included for a whole week of skiing, accommodation, food, transport and activities in Japan still can save you 1000 bucks in comparison or so. Especially now when the Yen is so cheap and the Euro is running away from the Dollar. I think the demand will shift from European skiing to Japanese skiing. 

Sapporo is also an up and coming tourism city in Japan after Tokyo, Kyoto and Osaka is so severely overcrowded with tourists due to the record low Yen that many complain it doesn’t have that Japanese magic anymore because you see more tourists than Japanese people in most areas. So many choose Sapporo instead for the authentic Japanese experience people say is like visiting Japan in the 1990s but in 2026!

So with this in mind, I think demand can be ramped up. Especially during winter.","author":"@S33SAW33","authorIsChannelOwner":false,"replyCount":0,"voteCount":3,"hasCreatorHeart":true,"videoId":"X9fBANydYpo","pageUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/shorts/X9fBANydYpo","commentsCount":7,"title":"Air Canada's Shortest Asia Route Makes No Sense #aviation #airline"}

{"cid":"UgxGlETIznB7Tm28XvN4AaABAg","replyToCid":null,"type":"comment","publishedTimeText":"1 day ago","comment":"We recently flew from BHX to PMI (Well should have). The aircraft arrived on-time inbound but ended up with a tech fault. Within about 30 minutes of being informed, we received an email and text for a self-service platform, our only complaint was it tried to push us to just accept a refund. But we selected new flights, due to a lack of flights from BHX to PMI, we selected LGW to PMI, it then let us select a hotel, but most were some distance from LGW, so we decided to decline and claim our own hotel. We travelled down to Gatwick, claimed the train, hotel easyJet paid within 4 weeks. 

Very impressed - compared to some of the issues we have had with "Full Service" who do not use technology. 

I can imagine easyJet would have been a challenge if we were not okay with technology.","author":"@RonanandAlex","authorIsChannelOwner":false,"replyCount":0,"voteCount":1,"hasCreatorHeart":false,"videoId":"XQGfcDqjlVw","pageUrl":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XQGfcDqjlVw","commentsCount":122,"title":"Is EasyJet Still a Low Cost Carrier?"}
